{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01HRoqn2R87p9HV4w85u2XCZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_013VzgnmNUGxFAMwwjsAtpwX","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Cache keys generated from identical query parameters are always identical, and keys from different parameters never collide.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Key generation is a pure deterministic transformation — input parameters in, string key out. The failure mode (collision or non-determinism) lives entirely inside one function. No module handoff is required to expose it. REAL-INFRA: No OS, network, or subprocess involved. MOCK-HIDE: Nothing to mock; the function has no external dependencies. LLM-DEP: None. MULTI-STEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered but rejected because the failure (collision or inconsistency) cannot be caused by two modules interacting — it is contained within the key-generation algorithm itself.","test_description":"Call the key-generation function with the same query-parameter dict multiple times and assert identical output; then call it with a large set of distinct parameter dicts (varying types, orderings, edge-case values) and assert no two distinct inputs produce the same key.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The TTL for a cache entry is computed correctly based on the data category's configured freshness rule (e.g., user profiles = 5 minutes, product catalog = 1 hour).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: TTL computation is a deterministic lookup/calculation: given a data category and a config object, return a duration. The failure mode (wrong TTL returned) lives inside the computation function and cannot hide behind a module boundary. REAL-INFRA: No I/O; the config can be a plain in-process object. MOCK-HIDE: No external dependency whose mock could suppress a real failure. LLM-DEP: None. MULTI-STEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered but rejected because wiring the cache to a DB is irrelevant to whether the TTL formula or category dispatch is correct.","test_description":"Construct a freshness-rule configuration with known values for each data category. Call the TTL-computation function with each category and assert the exact expected duration. Also test an unrecognized category to verify the fallback/error behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is incorrect strategy selection: given a memory-usage value and a threshold config, return the wrong strategy. That logic lives inside one decision function. Caching layers almost always track their own byte-count internally rather than querying the OS, so the memory value is injectable. REAL-INFRA: No real OS memory probe needed — the test can supply a synthetic usage value above or below threshold. If the implementation does query OS-level memory (e.g., /proc/meminfo), the level rises to System; but the behavior text does not require that. MOCK-HIDE: Nothing external whose mock would hide the strategy-switch bug. LLM-DEP: None. MULTI-STEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: System was considered in case the implementation reads OS memory directly, but the behavior text ('configured threshold') is consistent with an internal counter, so Unit is the minimum.","test_description":"Instantiate the strategy-selector with a known threshold. Inject a memory-usage value just below the threshold and assert LRU is selected. Inject a value at and above the threshold and assert LFU is selected. Also verify the strategy reverts to LRU when usage drops back below threshold (if the implementation supports that).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.62,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode spans two modules: the DB-write path and the cache-invalidation path. A unit test of the invalidation function alone cannot catch a bug where the write path never triggers invalidation, or where the key-matching logic misidentifies affected rows. At least the cache module and its DB-change listener/adapter must be wired together. REAL-INFRA: If invalidation is triggered by application-level explicit calls after a write, an in-process fake DB (or a local embedded DB) reproduces the failure without real network PostgreSQL — Integration suffices. If the mechanism uses PostgreSQL LISTEN/NOTIFY or triggers, a real DB instance is required (System). The behavior text does not specify the mechanism, so Integration is the minimum; reviewers should upgrade to System if the implementation uses DB-level notification. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the cache at unit level hides whether the write path actually calls invalidate and whether the key-match logic covers all affected rows. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) Real network not strictly required if application-level invalidation; (b) no AI/ML; (c) no multiple agentic steps; (d) no LLM stages.","test_description":"Seed the in-process cache with several entries whose keys correspond to rows in a test table. Execute a write (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) against the test table through the full application write path. Assert that all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows are gone, and entries for unaffected rows remain intact.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"If the invalidation mechanism is DB-level (triggers, LISTEN/NOTIFY), upgrade to System and use a real PostgreSQL instance (e.g., via testcontainers).","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.38,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: LRU and LFU are self-contained data-structure algorithms. The failure mode (wrong entry evicted) is entirely inside the eviction data structure and selection logic — no external module handoff is needed to expose it. REAL-INFRA: No I/O; the cache can be instantiated in-process at a small fixed capacity. MOCK-HIDE: Nothing external to mock. LLM-DEP: None. MULTI-STEP: None. REJECTION-GATE: Integration was considered because eviction interacts with memory-pressure detection (behavior 3), but that interaction is not what this behavior tests — it tests correctness of the eviction selection algorithm itself, which is self-contained.","test_description":"Instantiate the cache at a known small capacity under each policy (LRU and LFU). For LRU: insert entries and access a subset in a specific order; fill the cache to trigger eviction and assert the least-recently-accessed entry was removed. For LFU: insert entries and access a subset with varying frequencies; fill the cache to trigger eviction and assert the least-frequently-accessed entry was removed. Cover tie-breaking behavior explicitly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.87,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10069,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0